Bring a large #pot{} of salted water to a boil. Wash and dry produce.

Trim and thinly slice @scallions{2}, separating whites from greens. Peel and mince
or grate @garlic{2%cloves}.

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{2%tsp} in a medium pot over high heat. Add
@coleslaw mix{4%oz} and cook, stirring constantly, until lightly charred,
~{1-2%minutes}. Transfer to a #plate{}.

Heat a drizzle of oil in pot used for cabbage over medium-high heat. Add scallion
whites and garlic; cook, stirring occasionally, until fragrant, ~{20-30%seconds}.

Add @ground pork{10%oz}, half the @sesame seeds{1%tbsp}, and @salt{1/4%tsp};
cook, breaking up meat into pieces, until browned and cooked through,
~{5-7%minutes}.

Once pork is done, add @Szechuan paste{2%tbsp} and @peanut butter{1.15%oz}; cook,
stirring occasionally, until lightly browned and combined, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Stir in @pork ramen stock concentrate{1}, @chicken stock concentrate{1}, and
@water{2 1/2%cups}. Bring to a boil, then reduce heat to low. Cook, stirring
occasionally, until slightly thickened, ~{2-4%minutes}. Taste and season with
@salt{} and @pepper{} if necessary.

Once salted water is boiling, add half the @ramen noodles{4.5%oz} to pot. Cook
until tender, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Drain noodles; rinse under cold water for ~{30%seconds}.

Divide noodles between large #soup bowls{}. Pour broth over noodles and top with
charred cabbage. Garnish with scallion greens, remaining sesame seeds, and
@chili flakes{1%tsp} to taste. Serve.

> Ground Pork is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 160°.